\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. S. wulfenii} Hoppe ex Mert. & Koch in Röhling, {\i Deutschl. Fl.} ed. 3, {\b 3}: 386 (1831). Stolons long, stout, woody. Rosettes 4-5(-9) cm in diameter; inner leaves connivent. Leaves c. 30 × 12 mm, oblong-spathulate, cuspidate, glabrous except for cilia, glaucous; margins somewhat involute towards the apex. Flowering stem 15-25 cm. Flowers 11- to 15-merous; petals 10 × 1-2 mm, lemon-yellow, with a basal purple spot; filaments purple. 1500-2700{\i  m; usually calcifuge.  • E. Alps; N.W. Jugoslavia. }Au He It Ju.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  wulfenii}: Rosette-leaves glabrous on both surfaces. 2n = 36.{\i  E. Alps}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp.{\b  juvanii} (Strgar) Favarger & J. Parnell, {\i Bot. Jour. Linn. Soc.}{\b  103}: 217 (1990) ({\i S. juvanii} Strgar): Rosette-leaves glandular-pubescent on both surfaces. 2n = 36. {\i  E. Slovenja}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. S. grandiflorum} Haw.,{\i  Revis. Pl. Succ.} 66 (1821) ({\i S. gaudinii} Christ). Stolons 10-20 cm, stout. Rosettes 2-5 cm in diameter, rather lax and flat. Leaves oblong-cuneate, cuspidate, densely pubescent, dark green, with a reddish-brown apex, with strong resinous or foetid odour. Flowering stem 10-20 cm. Flowers 12- to 14-merous; petals 10-18 × 2-3 mm, yellow with a basal purple spot; filaments purple. 2n = 80.{\i  Calcifuge. • W.C. part of S. Alps, from Susa to Simplon.} He It.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. S. ciliosum} Craib,{\i  Kew Bull.}{\b  1914}: 379 (1914) ({\i S. borisii} Degen & Urum.). Stolons slender. Rosettes 2-3·5(-5) cm in diameter, depressed-globose. Leaves c. 10 × 4 mm, oblong-oblanceolate, acute, strongly incurved, pubescent, bearing towards the apex stiff cilia 2-4 mm long, which are interwoven with those of adjoining leaves. Flowering stem 4-10 cm. Flowers 12- to 14 merous; petals 10-12 × 1·5 mm, lemon-yellow; filaments white (rarely purple). 2n = 34. •{\i  Macedonia.} Bu Gr Ju.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The plants from the western end of the range (mountains S.E. of Ohrid) show some approach to{\b  4}.
\par

